<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<ecoSpold xmlns="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02 ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02.xsd http://www.EcoInvent.org/UsedUserMasterData ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02UserMasterData.xsd">
  <childActivityDataset>
    <activityDescription>
      <activity specialActivityType="0" id="2175e29c-322d-5a9d-8a8e-2b598efb3c7c" activityNameId="796110af-8e4a-42b1-abc7-2dcbc7a40fb2" parentActivityId="b4856bbf-f294-41bf-ad58-de15d675daec" inheritanceDepth="-1" type="1">
        <activityName xml:lang="en">methylcyclohexane production</activityName>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">hexahydrotoluene, cyclohexyl methane</synonym>
        <includedActivitiesStart xml:lang="en">The activity starts when the raw materials enter the process.</includedActivitiesStart>
        <includedActivitiesEnd xml:lang="en">The activity ends with methylcyclohexane being ready for further transformation or transportation at the production site gate. Materials entering the process are included as well as energy uses, infrastructure and emissions.
</includedActivitiesEnd>
        <generalComment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This dataset represents the production of 1 kg of methylcyclohexane by hydrogenation of toluene in the presence of Raney nickel catalyst.. </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">Methylcyclohexane (CAS-No. 108-87-2, C7H14, Synonyms: hexahydrotoluene, cyclohexyl methane) is a colorless transparent liquid with a faint, benzene-like odor. The primary use of methylcyclohexane is as a component in the feed to catalytic naphtha reformers where it is readily dehydrogenated to toluene, a high-octane motor gasoline component. Some methylcyclohexane is used for solvent applications in which it is one component of a narrow boiling range fraction of naphtha, but no current market exists for large-scale quantities.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">In this dataset, the raw material inputs, and process-specific material exchanges, are modelled with a generic stoichiometry-based tool, using literature or estimated yields. The emissions are modelled with a default value, which is estimated based on losses, unreacted chemicals, among others. At the same time, the energy consumption is based on data from literature sources. Finally, the auxiliary (i.e., cooling water and infrastructure) exchanges are modelled with a default value based on industry data from literature sources. For more information on the calculations refer to the sampling procedure.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">Sutter, J. (2007) Life Cycle Inventories of Petrochemical Solvents. ecoinvent report No. 22. Swiss Centre for Life Cycle Inventories, Dübendorf, 2007.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">Campbell, M. L. 2011. Cyclohexane. Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry.</text>
        </generalComment>
      </activity>
      <classification classificationId="28f738cc-bb73-48f8-b633-f83fb9bc5ddc">
        <classificationSystem xml:lang="en">ISIC rev.4 ecoinvent</classificationSystem>
        <classificationValue xml:lang="en">2011:Manufacture of basic chemicals</classificationValue>
      </classification>
      <geography geographyId="7846b897-7c04-4f9f-b607-2b83fcd9a74c">
        <shortname xml:lang="en">RoW</shortname>
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">The inventory is modelled at the Global level. The main material inputs and outputs of this activity are generated with on a generic stoichiometry-based model, using literature or estimated yields.  Furthermore, the source of information for the heat and electricity inputs is literature data for the specific technology. Finally, the main source of information for the values for water (process and cooling), nitrogen, chemical factory is industry data from the GENDORF Chemical Park, which is based in Germany and produced an average of 2462760 tonnes of chemical substances in the years 2015-2019. For more information on the calculations refer to the sampling procedure. </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">The dataset could also be considered as not geography-specific, and thus, valid for a broader geographical coverage.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">Hischier, R. (2005) Establishing Life Cycle Inventories of Chemicals Based on Differing Data Availability (9 pp). The International Journal of Life Cycle Assessment, Volume 10, Issue 1, pp 59-67. 10.1065/lca2004.10.181.7 </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2016, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2017, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2020, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">Chauvel, Alain, Gilles Lefebvre, and L. Castex in "Petrochemical processes. Technical and economical characteristics Vol. 2." (1989)</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="8">Wurster, R., Zittel, W.: Hydrogen Energy in: "Energy technologies to reduce CO2 emissions in Europe: prospects, competition, synergy", Conference Proceeding of the Conference held at Petten, 11-12 April 1994, OECD/IEA, Paris 1994</text>
        </comment>
      </geography>
      <technology technologyLevel="3">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This dataset represents the hydrogentation of toluene. The hydrogentation of toluene is similar to the hydrogenation of benzene, with a yield of 95%. (Ullmann 2004). At the same time, the catalyst assumed is Raney nickel (50 % Ni, 50 % Al). As there was no data available for the heat requirments of the methylcyclohexane production, the values were estimated with data for the production of cyclohexane from the hydrogenation of benzene (Chauvel et al. 1989). At the same time, the electricity requirments of the toluene hydrogenations are based on the methylcyclohexane production of a plant in Germany (Wurster 1994).</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">Hydrogenation of toluene:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">C7H8 + 3H2 --&gt; C7H14</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">In this dataset, a yield of 95% was assumed.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">Ullmann's encyclopedia of industrial chemistry (2004).</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">Wurster, R., Zittel, W.: Hydrogen Energy in: "Energy technologies to reduce CO2 emissions in Europe: prospects, competition, synergy", Conference Proceeding of the Conference held at Petten, 11-12 April 1994, OECD/IEA, Paris 1994.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">Chauvel, Alain, Gilles Lefebvre, and L. Castex in "Petrochemical processes. Technical and economical characteristics Vol. 2." (1989)</text>
        </comment>
      </technology>
      <timePeriod startDate="1989-01-01" endDate="2023-12-31" isDataValidForEntirePeriod="true">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">The time period spans from the earliest year from which at least one of the input values was obtained until 2022, but overall form the most realistic picture of the production. Besides, the activity is partly generated, in terms of material inputs and outputs, based on a generic stoichiometry-based model, using literature or estimated yields, which does not expect to change over time.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">The source of information for the heat and electricity inputs is literature data (from 1989 and 1994) for the specific technology. Finally, the main source of information for the values for water (process and cooling), nitrogen, chemical factory is industry data from the GENDORF Chemical Park. The values are a 5-year average of data from 2015 to 2019 published by the GENDORF Chemical Park, which is based in Germany and produced an average of 2462760 tonnes of chemical substances in the years 2015-2019. The end time period is therefore set based on the years from Gendorf reference.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">For more information on the calculations refer to the sampling procedure and in the comments of the exchanges.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">Hischier, R. (2005) Establishing Life Cycle Inventories of Chemicals Based on Differing Data Availability (9 pp). The International Journal of Life Cycle Assessment, Volume 10, Issue 1, pp 59-67. 10.1065/lca2004.10.181.7 </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2016, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2017, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2020, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="8">Chauvel, Alain, Gilles Lefebvre, and L. Castex in "Petrochemical processes. Technical and economical characteristics Vol. 2." (1989)</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="9">Wurster, R., Zittel, W.: Hydrogen Energy in: "Energy technologies to reduce CO2 emissions in Europe: prospects, competition, synergy", Conference Proceeding of the Conference held at Petten, 11-12 April 1994, OECD/IEA, Paris 1994</text>
        </comment>
      </timePeriod>
      <macroEconomicScenario macroEconomicScenarioId="d9f57f0a-a01f-42eb-a57b-8f18d6635801">
        <name xml:lang="en">Business-as-Usual</name>
      </macroEconomicScenario>
    </activityDescription>
